10:55.989 --> 11:00.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Police say the
attack was planned
here, a historic neighborhood in
Istanbul

11:00.627 --> 11:06.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
called Fatih. The three suicide
bombers lived
in this second-floor apartment
before that

11:06.866 --> 11:13.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
attack. Turkish news media here
report that
neighbors complained of a
suspicious chemical

11:13.273 --> 11:15.608 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
odor coming from the building.

11:15.642 --> 11:20.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Turkish government says the
three men
were from Russia and the central
Asian countries

11:20.580 --> 11:27.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Kyrgyzstan and Uzbekistan,
and that it
was an ISIS operation. Reactions
to Tuesday's

11:27.320 --> 11:33.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
attack reflect how polarized
Turkey's population
is. Some locals in Istanbul told
the "NewsHour"

11:34.027 --> 11:38.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they don't think the government
is doing everything
it can to keep them safe.

11:38.565 --> 11:42.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): I
don't think they
do enough. With this last
attack, there is

11:42.502 --> 11:46.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not much they can do. They
tried, but they
made it worse. They cannot
control it.

11:46.739 --> 11:49.442 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Others are
staunch defenders
of the government.

11:49.475 --> 11:53.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): The
opposition,
they don't know anything. They
just talk.

11:53.680 --> 11:58.851 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JANE FERGUSON: Turkey's
president, Recep Tayyip
Erdogan, has been criticized in
the past for

11:58.885 --> 12:04.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tolerating the Islamic State's
use of the
country as a backdoor into
Syria. ISIS recruits

12:05.024 --> 12:10.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have often traveled through
Turkey on their
way to join the group. It's an
issue that's

12:10.663 --> 12:12.665 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
led to backlash in the streets.

12:12.699 --> 12:16.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator): We
think we are
surviving by chance, because the
government

12:16.636 --> 12:21.207 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
supports ISIS, and innocent
people are killed
as a result. We are here for the
innocent

12:21.240 --> 12:23.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people who were killed yesterday
at the Ataturk
Airport.

12:23.476 --> 12:27.847 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JANE FERGUSON: Now the
government is under
renewed pressure to react to the
attacks,

12:27.880 --> 12:33.553 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in part by thawing relations
with Russia.
Erdogan has called for Syria's
President Bashar

12:33.586 --> 12:39.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
al-Assad to step down, and had
been angered
by Russia's support of the
dictator.

12:39.425 --> 12:45.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last year, Turkish jets downed a
Russian plane
accused of entering their
airspace from Syria.

12:45.164 --> 12:51.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Turkish analysts say Ankara
increasingly
sees Russia as an important
partner, not only

12:52.005 --> 12:53.773 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in the fight against ISIS.

12:53.806 --> 12:58.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BORA BAYRAKTAR, Istanbul Bilgi
University:
Russia provides balance for
Turkey. Turkey

12:58.444 --> 13:03.349 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
always need a power to balance
European and
American demands.

13:03.383 --> 13:11.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Those swings in
alliances continue,
as Syria's war tests country
after country,

13:11.524 --> 13:16.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and as front-line state Turkey
faces some
of the most daunting challenges
of all.

13:16.562 --> 13:25.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Jane
Ferguson
in Istanbul, Turkey.

13:25.071 --> 13:34.514 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to my
interview with the
U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations, Samantha

13:34.547 --> 13:36.315 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Power.

13:36.349 --> 13:43.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She was here in Washington
yesterday to speak
on the plight of refugees, now a
record 65

13:43.056 --> 13:47.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
million worldwide. I spoke with
her yesterday
afternoon at the State
Department.

13:47.927 --> 13:49.996 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ambassador Susan Power, thank
you very much
for talking with us.

13:50.029 --> 13:51.798 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SAMANTHA POWER, U.S. Ambassador
to the United
Nations: Great to be here.

13:51.831 --> 13:56.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You are calling
this situation
right now the greatest refugee
crisis the

13:56.602 --> 14:03.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
world has known since World War
II. And yet
you see this rising, enormous
backlash in

14:03.076 --> 14:07.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Europe, in the United States. It
says that
a lot of people, maybe most
people, don't

14:08.014 --> 14:11.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
share your view about what to
do. How do you
deal with that?

14:11.851 --> 14:17.490 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SAMANTHA POWER: Well, I think
there's a lot
of latent public opinion that
also doesn't

14:17.523 --> 14:22.695 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
necessarily get airtime during
presidential
elections, for instance.

14:22.729 --> 14:29.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there are fears. I think
those fears are
stoked. We have seen those in
history at different

14:29.035 --> 14:34.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
times, whether it's on whether
we let in Jewish
refugees during the Second World
War or Vietnamese

14:34.373 --> 14:36.476 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
refugees after the Vietnam War.

14:36.509 --> 14:42.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So there's nothing new in that
set of fears.
I think some of the fears are
warranted. People

14:42.749 --> 14:48.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are wondering, could ISIL
potentially sneak
through? And we have to answer
those fears.

14:48.087 --> 14:54.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think we have by putting
in place these
incredibly strenuous vetting
processes that

14:54.727 --> 14:59.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have the FBI and the Center for
Counterterrorism
and the Department of Homeland
Security at

14:59.899 --> 15:02.268 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the table vetting the time it
takes.

15:02.301 --> 15:07.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we also need to do a better
job lifting
up, I think, the voices of those
people who,

15:07.206 --> 15:12.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
again, aren't necessarily
running for office,
but who have welcomed refugees
into their

15:12.211 --> 15:16.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
homes, into their communities,
or giving small
amounts of money, donating toys.
And I see

15:16.315 --> 15:19.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that all over the place in going
to meet with
refugees around the country, is
just how much

15:19.652 --> 15:21.387 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
generosity there is at the same
time.

15:21.420 --> 15:26.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But you also see,
of course,
the vote in the United Kingdom
to leave the

15:26.125 --> 15:32.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
E.U., the Brexit vote. You see
Chancellor
Merkel in Germany facing
growing, significant

15:32.665 --> 15:34.534 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
opposition.

15:34.567 --> 15:38.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This has become a political
crisis or problem,
as much as a humanitarian one.
How much harder

15:38.971 --> 15:40.673 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
does that make it for you?

15:40.706 --> 15:44.110 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SAMANTHA POWER: Clearly, there
are difficult
politics associated with this
issue.

15:44.143 --> 15:49.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think we have to be a little
careful to
choose -- to pull out of Brexit
one thing

15:49.582 --> 15:54.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and say, wow, those people voted
that way
because of the Syrian refugee
crisis or because

15:54.887 --> 15:59.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of displacement. I mean, there
were concerns,
of course, that we saw in exit
polls and heard

15:59.592 --> 16:05.064 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from people about immigration,
so I don't
dismiss the point at all.

16:05.097 --> 16:10.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, you know, I think that part
of what is
making people feel a little
overwhelmed now,

16:10.770 --> 16:16.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
just by reading the newspaper,
is a sense
of an uncontrolled flow, just
people tumbling

16:16.542 --> 16:20.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
over borders. And that's also
where the security
fears -- people are asking,
well, could -- among

16:21.013 --> 16:27.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that population of ISIL in
Syria, couldn't
they be smuggled into that very
large number

16:27.353 --> 16:29.055 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of people?

16:29.088 --> 16:34.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what we're trying to do is
to say we have
systems here. We have processes.
In order

16:34.493 --> 16:38.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for those systems to work, there
has to be
burden-sharing. It has to be
more equitable.

16:38.130 --> 16:44.136 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It can't just be falling to
Turkey to take
three million Syrians, and then
have countries

16:44.170 --> 16:46.973 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
washing their hands of an
obligation to take
any.

16:47.006 --> 16:50.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If there's a way to -- and it's
very difficult
to do, but to sort of slow down
the process,

16:50.977 --> 16:55.214 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to make sure that the screening
and the procedures
are in place, to be sure that
communities

16:55.248 --> 16:59.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are ready to absorb refugees
when they land,
because there's nothing worse
than the volatility

16:59.752 --> 17:06.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of an unready community, you
know, meeting
an influx of families who have
gone through

17:06.092 --> 17:07.860 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
so much.

17:07.894 --> 17:10.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But it sounds
like what you're
saying is you're calling on
leaders to go

17:10.196 --> 17:14.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
against the popular will in
their countries,
because there are these -- as
you just said,

17:14.467 --> 17:20.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there are very real concerns in
this country
that so many of these refugees
may be terrorists

17:20.873 --> 17:24.043 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hiding or pretending to be
somebody else.

17:24.076 --> 17:27.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SAMANTHA POWER: This is an issue
that has
proven divisive, there's no
question.

17:27.880 --> 17:36.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I, again, draw on the number
of mayors
and local officials and school
board heads

17:36.188 --> 17:41.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who -- and private sector CEOs
who have gone
out of their way in this country
to say we

17:41.761 --> 17:45.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
want refugees. We have seen how
refugees work.
We have seen how they enrich our
community.

17:45.631 --> 17:49.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think, again, we just --
we just have
to know that there's more
beneath the surface

17:49.302 --> 17:51.003 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
than necessarily meets the eye.

17:51.037 --> 17:54.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: At the same time,
Americans
-- many Americans are looking at
this from

17:54.440 --> 17:59.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a -- frankly, a more parochial
standpoint.
They're thinking these people
may be taking

17:59.178 --> 18:05.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
jobs away from us. They may be
presenting
a very real security threat to
us right now.

18:05.651 --> 18:08.854 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can you guarantee the American
people those
things aren't going to happen?

18:08.888 --> 18:14.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SAMANTHA POWER: Well, what I can
say is that,
since September 11, we have
taken 800,000

18:14.360 --> 18:17.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people into this country in our
resettlement
program and not one of them has
been involved

18:17.663 --> 18:19.532 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in domestic terrorism.

18:19.565 --> 18:24.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What I can say is that our
system for screening
refugees is the most robust of
any for anybody

18:24.904 --> 18:30.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
coming into the country, and
that Syrian refugees
get an added layer of vetting
because of the

18:30.910 --> 18:33.646 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
proximity, of course, with a
battleground
and with ISIL.

18:33.679 --> 18:37.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You're probably
the person
in this administration at a high
level most

18:37.416 --> 18:42.722 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
identified with the humanitarian
cause, certainly
because of all the work you did
on humanitarian

18:42.755 --> 18:45.591 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
issues before you came into the
administration.

18:45.624 --> 18:51.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How do you square that with what
has to be,
I mean, from your perspective, a
disappointing

18:51.964 --> 18:54.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
response on the part of the
U.S.? I guess
the U.S. at this point has taken
in just a

18:54.600 --> 18:55.601 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
few thousand...

18:55.634 --> 18:57.103 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SAMANTHA POWER: Syrians.

18:57.136 --> 18:58.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: ... Syrian --
Syrian refugees
out of over -- of millions.

18:58.604 --> 18:59.705 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SAMANTHA POWER: Yes. Yes.

18:59.739 --> 19:01.941 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you
reconcile that personally?

19:01.974 --> 19:09.615 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SAMANTHA POWER: Well, I
reconcile it in part
because nobody is the more vocal
champion

19:09.648 --> 19:14.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of enhancing our support for
refugees than
the president I get to work for
every day.

19:14.153 --> 19:19.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So we have now increased the
number of refugees
we're taking this year to
85,000, including

19:19.725 --> 19:25.865 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
10,000 Syrians. We are
increasing next year
then to 100,000. That is a 40
percent increase

19:25.898 --> 19:30.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in just a two-year period of
time. We have
got to make sure the system is
ready, and

19:30.569 --> 19:34.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that we can do the vetting
consistent with
our primary responsibility,
which is to keep

19:34.774 --> 19:36.609 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the American people safe.

19:36.642 --> 19:41.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Of course, the
root cause of
the most of the Syrian refugee
crisis is the

19:41.847 --> 19:46.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
war ongoing there. And just
recently, a number
of U.S. diplomats wrote a letter
to Secretary

19:47.019 --> 19:52.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Kerry saying they want the U.S.
very much
to take a more aggressive
military role in

19:52.925 --> 19:53.926 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that war.

19:53.959 --> 19:56.395 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How do you -- what's your
feeling about that?

19:56.429 --> 20:02.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SAMANTHA POWER: The views
expressed in that
cable are views and policy
positions that

20:02.701 --> 20:08.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have been taken in meetings I'm
in, in meetings
the president has chaired. I
mean, he welcomes

20:08.307 --> 20:10.009 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that kind of debate.

20:10.042 --> 20:14.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If we were able to present
something that
makes a compelling case, where,
you know,

20:14.313 --> 20:20.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the benefits in terms of ending
the Syrian
war are going to exceed the
costs, he's going

20:20.686 --> 20:25.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to embrace that. And there's not
an option
that's been presented, again,
that he hasn't

20:25.257 --> 20:32.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
embraced, you know, that if
somebody presents
it in a manner where it is
compelling and

20:32.965 --> 20:36.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
actually looks like it's going
to solve the
problem, he's going to be all
over it.

20:36.902 --> 20:41.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And to this day, even with the
short time
left in his tenure, we are still
looking to

20:41.540 --> 20:44.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
end the war, and we are still
being encouraged
to look under every rock.

20:44.977 --> 20:52.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: U.S. Ambassador
to the United
Nations Samantha Power, thank
you very much.

20:52.751 --> 20:56.889 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SAMANTHA POWER: Thank you.

