as. So, they only had pencil and
paper, and

41:47.572 --> 41:52.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these really loud mechanical
calculators that
couldn't do very much. And, from
that, they

41:53.010 --> 41:57.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were able to calculate an
incredible number
of trajectories for spacecraft,
propellants.

41:57.515 --> 42:01.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So they are
literally computing
and called computers.

42:01.419 --> 42:02.653 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: Exactly, yes.

42:02.687 --> 42:05.022 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Before the age
that we are
now living in.

42:05.056 --> 42:09.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: But then, once
the first IBMs
came in, then they became the
first computer

42:09.594 --> 42:11.329 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
programmers in the lab.

42:11.362 --> 42:14.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What kind of
backgrounds did
they come from that brought them
into this?

42:14.565 --> 42:18.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: So, they come
from different
backgrounds. Many of them have
only had high

42:18.936 --> 42:22.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
school degrees. But they were
exceptionally
good at math. So, they were
often the only

42:22.974 --> 42:26.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
girls in their math classes, but
they would
-- they loved math. They would
take as much

42:26.844 --> 42:28.513 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
as they could.

42:28.546 --> 42:32.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they're weren't very many
options for
women then. Mostly, if you loved
math, if

42:32.383 --> 42:38.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you loved science, your options
still were
nurse, teacher, secretary. And
so, by becoming

42:38.156 --> 42:41.592 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a computer, they could get
around this and
have a job in science.

42:41.626 --> 42:46.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Give us an
example, someone
that you came to know and love,
because you

42:46.631 --> 42:48.132 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
told these individual stories,
right?

42:48.166 --> 42:51.169 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: I did. I found
these women
and I loved speaking with them.

42:51.202 --> 42:53.004 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes. Yes.

42:53.037 --> 42:57.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: A wonderful
example is Barbara
Paulson. Today, she is turning
88. She has

42:57.375 --> 43:03.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a birthday. And she started in
the lab when
she was 19. She had her high
school degree

43:03.080 --> 43:08.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and loved math. And she had an
incredible,
long career. She had a 45-year
career at NASA,

43:08.119 --> 43:09.654 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
working on all of these
different missions.

43:09.687 --> 43:13.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What kind of
limitations do
they run up against?

43:13.891 --> 43:18.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: These women, they
were obviously
paid less than the men, and
their responsibilities

43:18.963 --> 43:23.134 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
increased as the time went by,
but still they
had many setbacks.

43:23.167 --> 43:26.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, of course, there was sexism
there, as
there is today in science, so
they had to

43:26.871 --> 43:33.177 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cope with that. But, in general,
they loved
their careers, they loved their
time at NASA,

43:33.211 --> 43:35.079 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and really had such a big
contribution.

43:35.112 --> 43:38.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You described
them sort of
joining -- sort of like forming
a club. I

43:38.583 --> 43:40.017 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
suppose that they almost had to.

43:40.051 --> 43:42.220 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: They really
relied on each
other.

43:42.253 --> 43:46.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They had -- so they became this
all-woman
group because of Macie Roberts.
So she was

43:46.991 --> 43:52.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the first supervisor of the
computers. She
was made supervisor in 1942, and
so she is

43:52.697 --> 43:57.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the one that decided it should
be all women,
even though men did apply, but
she wanted

43:57.435 --> 43:59.403 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it to be a close-knit group of
girls.

43:59.437 --> 44:01.138 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: She kept out the
men?

44:01.172 --> 44:02.940 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: She did, on
purpose.

44:02.974 --> 44:04.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Now, that's an
interesting
-- so a reverse discrimination
in a sense.

44:04.075 --> 44:05.843 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NATHALIA HOLT: Yes.

44:05.877 --> 44:10.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then this actually continued
for decades.
Then their friends, as well as
co-workers,

44:10.214 --> 44:14.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they had just spent so much time
together,
often all night during missions.
They were

44:14.318 --> 44:17.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there for days sometimes in some
of these
missions.

44:17.855 --> 44:23.728 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And there were also some
concerns that a male
wouldn't do as well taking
directions from

44:23.761 --> 44:24.996 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a female boss.

44:25.029 --> 44:26.464 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But what kind of
things were
they working on?

44:26.497 --> 44:28.699 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
NATHALIA HOLT: There are
thrilling moments.

44:28.733 --> 44:33.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of my favorite is during
Explorer 1, which
is the first American satellite.
And here

44:33.437 --> 44:37.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you have Barbara Paulson, who is
in the control
room that night. She has worked
in the lab

44:38.009 --> 44:42.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for a decade already. And so she
had been
hard at work making this moment
possible,

44:42.580 --> 44:45.182 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
getting all of the rockets to
this point.

44:45.216 --> 44:49.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And she is the one calculating
the trajectory
that night. So, when the first
American satellite

44:49.854 --> 44:54.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is a success, its because of
her. She is the
one that found out it's actually
in orbit.

44:54.959 --> 44:59.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Did she get her
due? Did she
get -- did people understand it
at the time?

44:59.230 --> 45:04.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: This is a very
sad part of
the book, is that, although she
was celebrated

45:04.402 --> 45:09.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
then, and she had a room full of
people who
were so excited by what she had
accomplished,

45:09.073 --> 45:11.809 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what I found is that much of
that was forgotten.

45:11.842 --> 45:18.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, in 2008, NASA held a gala in
celebration
of Explorer 1 for the 50th
anniversary. And

45:18.549 --> 45:22.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
none of the women who worked on
that project,
who were even in mission control
that night,

45:22.954 --> 45:25.189 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
were invited. And this is a very
sad thing.

45:25.222 --> 45:26.290 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: This is in 2008.

45:26.324 --> 45:27.458 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NATHALIA HOLT: Yes.

45:27.491 --> 45:30.528 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So the awareness
has not changed
at all?

45:30.561 --> 45:32.229 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: Yes, it is very
sad.

45:32.263 --> 45:36.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But my hope is that, now, they
will finally
get the recognition that they
deserve.

45:36.334 --> 45:41.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: We do a lot of
talking on our
program looking at the problem
of young girls,

45:42.006 --> 45:47.845 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
young women, women getting into
and then staying
in, staying with sciences.

45:47.878 --> 45:48.779 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NATHALIA HOLT: Yes.

45:48.813 --> 45:50.181 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What do you see
happening?

45:50.214 --> 45:52.883 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: It's a desperate
time for women
in technology.

45:52.917 --> 45:54.151 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: A desperate time?

45:54.185 --> 45:55.953 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: Absolutely.

45:55.987 --> 46:00.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, in 1987 -- 1984 -- excuse me
-- 37 percent
of bachelor's degrees in
computer sciences

46:00.791 --> 46:05.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were awarded to women. And today
that number
is 18 percent. So it's a huge
drop.

46:05.997 --> 46:07.865 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Why do you think
that's happened?

46:07.898 --> 46:11.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: Some of the
reasons are education.
Some of them have to do with the
lack of role

46:11.702 --> 46:16.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
models that young women can see,
they can
see a reflection of themselves
in computer

46:16.407 --> 46:18.709 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
science.

46:18.743 --> 46:23.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it's important that we
address this, because
even for the women in science
today, we're

46:23.547 --> 46:26.951 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
seeing that about half of the
women leave
mid-career.

46:26.984 --> 46:33.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What I like about the stories of
these women,
the Rocket Girls, is that they
were able to

46:33.190 --> 46:42.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
get over many of these hurdles
through -- it
wasn't typical for women to be
mothers and

46:42.133 --> 46:44.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
scientist at this time. And they
were able
to accomplish that.

46:44.835 --> 46:48.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What about in the
space program
itself? The situation for women
has -- well,

46:48.973 --> 46:51.208 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it has changed dramatically from
the period
you're writing about.

46:51.242 --> 46:52.309 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: It has changed
dramatically.

46:52.343 --> 46:52.843 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

46:52.877 --> 46:54.812 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NATHALIA HOLT: Yes.

46:54.845 --> 46:59.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So what we are seeing is that
for women astronauts,
this is an amazing time. We're
saying half

46:59.283 --> 47:01.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the class of astronauts at
NASA today are
women.

47:01.452 --> 47:03.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I read that half
of the class,
yes, yes. That's striking.

47:03.454 --> 47:05.189 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NATHALIA HOLT: Yes.

47:05.222 --> 47:08.626 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is an incredible
accomplishment.
And we should all be very proud
of this. But

47:08.659 --> 47:13.998 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for the engineers who are part
of the space
agency, it is a different story.
And it's

47:14.031 --> 47:17.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one that we need to make sure
that we are
bolstering these women and
encouraging girls

47:17.601 --> 47:19.203 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
today to go into the sciences.

47:19.236 --> 47:21.906 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, the
"Rise of the
Rocket Girls."

47:21.939 --> 47:24.575 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Nathalia Holt, thank you so
much.

47:24.608 --> 47:31.382 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NATHALIA HOLT: Thank you.

47:31.415 --> 47:39.156 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to another in
our Brief
But Spectacular series, where we
ask interesting

47:39.190 --> 47:41.192 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
people to describe their
passions.

47:41.225 --> 47:46.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we hear from comedian
Tig Notaro,
who has used her performances to
overcome

47:46.797 --> 47:52.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
enormous personal hurdles,
including a cancer
diagnoses and the loss of her
mother.

47:52.636 --> 47:56.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Her memoir, "I'm Just a Person,"
came out
earlier this month.

47:56.507 --> 48:03.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TIG NOTARO, Comedian: In 2012, I
was so busy.
I was filming a movie, shooting
a TV pilot.

48:03.848 --> 48:09.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Then I started to get sick, and
I got diagnosed
with pneumonia. A few days
later, my mother

48:09.286 --> 48:12.356 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tripped and hit her head and
died.

48:12.390 --> 48:21.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My girlfriend at the time, she
and I split
up. And then I was diagnosed
with invasive

48:21.232 --> 48:23.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
bilateral breast cancer.

48:23.334 --> 48:29.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
During that time period, I kept
hearing, "God
never gives you more than you
can handle."

48:29.106 --> 48:33.611 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That was way more than I could
handle.

48:33.644 --> 48:44.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would hear brave and battling
and all of
these words that I didn't know
that I really

48:44.188 --> 48:52.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
related to. And I kept picturing
the military
hearing about this brave person
and just kicking

48:52.763 --> 49:00.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
my door down and coming in to
find me just
crying on my couch for my mommy,
and them

49:00.905 --> 49:06.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
being like: Yes, there she is.
We need you
on the front lines. There's the
brave one.

49:06.043 --> 49:14.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That diagnosis just sent me
spiraling, but
also I felt more prolific than
ever. I started

49:14.418 --> 49:21.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
writing nonstop. And I had a
show coming up.
I knew I need an opening line
that was going

49:21.058 --> 49:26.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to crack the tension. I had this
thought that
went through my head picturing
myself walking

49:26.197 --> 49:28.332 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
out, saying:

49:28.365 --> 49:36.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Good evening. Hello. I have
cancer. How are
you? Hi. How are you? Is
everyone having a

49:36.540 --> 49:41.846 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
good time? I have cancer. How
are you?

49:41.879 --> 49:50.020 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There were so many mixed
responses, from just
stunned silence, to
uncomfortable laughing,

49:50.054 --> 49:51.755 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to crying.

49:51.789 --> 49:58.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To some degree, I was asking for
help, even
while I was trying to make light
of it.

49:58.195 --> 50:04.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When I had a double mastectomy,
I didn't have
reconstructive surgery, and I
don't have nipples.

50:04.902 --> 50:09.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was -- you know, it was a
struggle
getting comfortable with myself.
But when

50:09.573 --> 50:21.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I really thought about how it
was just my
skin growing together with my
skin and healing

50:21.986 --> 50:29.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
me, why is that uncomfortable or
shameful
or embarrassing or something to
hide?

50:29.927 --> 50:35.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If somebody has a scar on their
face, nobody's
like, hey, you need to cover
that. That's

50:35.432 --> 50:42.139 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hard to look at. After I really
healed and
was comfortable with my body and
was back

50:42.172 --> 50:46.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
touring in front of audiences, I
kept thinking,
oh, my God, I could take my
shirt off right

50:46.744 --> 50:48.712 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
now and blow these people's
minds.

50:48.746 --> 50:53.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I couldn't take it any longer,
and I just
had to -- I had to remove my
shirt.

50:53.784 --> 51:01.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People say things to me now, oh,
this is so
empowering for women and cancer
survivors,

51:01.091 --> 51:10.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and -- absolutely. It's really
more about
just being human beings. And
this is our body.

51:10.501 --> 51:12.436 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And who cares?

51:12.469 --> 51:19.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My name is Tig Notaro, and this
is my Brief
But Spectacular take on healing
through comedy.

